** General Strategy

- when one knows that we lack the assets for slam (regardless if controls are good), or controls are known to be missing
  then sign off - a basic principle!
- slam trys opposite a very limited hand are serious, that is not highly speculative, so when slam is possible opposite
  a perfect minimum range hand
- serious slam trys opposite very limited hands imply that we have the assets for slam and that only controls matter
- very limited hands should therefore show controls below the trump suit and not worry about extra values
- somewhat limited hands (e.g. 11--15) can e.g. bypass 4M with some extras and a missing control
- somewhat limited hands (e.g. 11--15?) may skip control showing if minimum and bad fitting
- neither cue bids nor last train show better hands than the other, flexibility is needed to get the most useful
  information
- skipping cue bids up the line to use last train would usually imply someone has a wide range and so it's a more
  quantitative ask
- after both partners cue bid, should we last train at all? perhaps only if both are ambiguous wide ranging? how wide?
- splinters usually imply a hand that won't go to slam without a fitting hand from partner - consider if bidding on
  regardless that maybe it's best to find a way to control bid without revealing your shape, however, maybe the fitting
  hand was required for the grand slam and not the small slam
- statistically do not expect a splinter to line up well against a strong 20+ balanced hand - it is likely they have
  some wasted values, though you maybe ok opposite a shapely hand (e.g. Acol 2) that is more based on tricks
- the responder to a splinter can go on with enough extras despite not fitting (e.g. ~13+ opening values outside splinter suit)
- the cue bidding style means we do not show shortage in partner's suit, even though with a big trump fit it can make sense
- supporting partner's suit after agreeing a different trump suit is natural double fit finding if we have only shown 2 suits
- with only the trump suit shown, the first slam try control bid is honour showing
- 3N is natural, not serious in only a few specific situations, e.g. 1M--2N--3C--3N

** What is 4N?

Natural quantitative, to play, ace asking, key card asking, takeout or other?


*** Minor Agreed 4N

- jump 4N by FITTING KNOWN WEAK hand (after slam try) - excellent trumps/extra length, NO side A/K
- jump 4N - quantitative (minor already agreed so can use Redwood/Minorwood)
- GF, non-jump 4N with LIMITED hand - natural, to play
- GF, non-jump 4N with both slam going UNLIMITED (be sure not limited) hand AND when Redwood RKB ask free - substitute control bid
- GF, non-jump 4N UNLIMITED and no space for Redwood (rarer, after control bids) - [RKB](#RKB 4N)
- after [Redwood](#Redwood for minors) then conditional King or Queen ask
- GF, rare (usually lower DRKB ask), both minors supported, or 5--5+ opposite known balanced hand - [Double Fit RKB](#Double Fit RKB)

Additionally, with higher COMPETITION by 4th/2nd+4th where 4m or Redwood maybe needed as purely competitive or natural
bids. This is rarer in limited opening systems because it's harder to agree minors before interference and the opening
hand is more limited (though resopnder maybe unlimited).

- non-GF competitive situation, JUMP CHEAPEST UNBID SUIT else JUMP 4N after COMPETITION when *4m is just competitive* -
  [RKB](#RKB 4N) even though this can be annoyingly high. The jump cheapest unbid replaces things like splinters or even
  EKB. Competition turns off some splinters/EKB type stuff

*** Major Agreed/Implied 4N

- two suits naturally supported, at least one major, or 5--5+ opposite known balanced hand - [Double Fit RKB](#Double Fit RKB)
- raised or set suit - [RKB](#RKB 4N)
- implied long excellent 6+ suit (eg. 3 level jump overcall or 3M+ opening) - [RKB](#RKB 4N)

*** 1 Major by 1 Partner Each

Both partners bidding a different major, which takes priority?

- 4N bidder's (asker's) suit is priority when can GF explicitly to set partner's major (e.g. 1S--2H--2S--3S), so 1S--2H--2S--4N is !h RKB
- otherwise LAST BID major, e.g. 1S--2H--3S--4N cannot explicit set (also here 3!s is "long excellent 6+ suit implied")

You might argue that 1S--2H--2S--3H can force further and set !hs before bidding 4N, and therefore just treat 4N as
quantitative. However, 1S--2H--2S--3H--3S now leaves !ss as last bid major.

*** 1 Minor by 1 Partner Each

Both partners bidding a different minor.

- rare situations where 4m as Q-Minorwood not available for both the minors
- 4m is Q-Minorwood where available
- 4th or unbid suit is RKB for the other minor, a weird Redwood-like situation
- 4N is quantitative

2C--3C--3S = quasi natural game accept after 3C !d transfer
    4C = NF natural, stop problems
    4D = [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood)
    4H = !c RKB
    4S = extras 3 card raise, play suggestion, else try 5m

*** Others 4N

- Partner *never* bid - Takeout
- 1 minor then over jump 4 level interference - Takeout/Unusual
- jump 4N by MINOR agreed FITTING KNOWN WEAK hand (after slam try) - excellent trumps/extra length, NO side A/K
- jump response to Takeout double without interference - Quantitative
- jump 4N with all suits bid and no fit found - Quantitative
- jump 4N when we have an easy way to force and set suit major available (e.g. 1!s--2!d--2!s--4N), and NOT "1 Major by 1 Partner Each" (as above) - Quantitative
- 1N opened or overcalled, and no major set, and after non-slam try stayman/transfers - Quantitative
- NT natural bid raised (including "NT" bids by artificial means) - Quantitative
- non-jump 4N with limited hand - natural, to play
- 4 level jump interference after long natural major/minor (1!h/!s or 2!c/!d) - [RKB](#RKB 4N)
- Opponent's open 2x/3x/4x preempt and partner overcalls - advancer [RKB](#RKB 4N)

** Quantitative 4N Responses

Just bid 6 if accept right? That's the default, but we can give 5N more nuance - anywhere responder can have reasonable
trick taking power / running suits but controls and hcp maybe light.

We can also optionally look for a fit with up the line Baron bids of 4+ card suits, after which 5N can be a final place
to play.

4N = quantitative
  P = no
  5x = optional Baron up the line suits
    5N = (later) to play
  5N = yes, but I have only max 1 Ace
  6N = accept


** Q-Minorwood

Quantitative Minorwood - bidding the 4 level minor trump suit as RKB with quantitative step. Let's responder give an
opinion on whether they have a worse or better slam going hand, the initial step response simply being a "reject".

Note, similar but higher, is (optional) "Auto RKB" where we pass 4N if minimum, otherwise respond as RKB.

- next step rejects, follow up is RKB
- higher bid auto RKB, accept slam try

i.e with natural bidding:

4C = natural, showing !cs
    4D = reject slam try
        4H = RKB anyway
    4H = 1/4 KC, RKB responses
    4S = 3/0 KC
    4N = 2/5 KC
    5C = 2/5 KC + Queen

4D = natural, !ds
    4H = reject slam try
        4S = RKB anyway
    4S = 1/4 KC, RKB responses
    4N = 3/0 KC
    5C = 2/5 KC
    5D = 2/5 KC + Queen

WHEN is 4m actually Q-Minorwood?

- (a) when is it on versus a flattish limited hand?
- (b) when is it on versus an unbalanced hand?
- just forcing, offering control or natural bidding if neither (a) nor (b) apply

*** 4CD vs Balanced/Defined Hands

Where *all* apply:

- (1) one hand shows a limited (fairly defined) flattish hand. E.g 2N opening/rebid/overcall, 1N opening. Such a hand is
  unlikely to need to describe their own suits
- (2) the partner shows a minor suit slam try at the 4 level (making agreeing and using something like Redwood impractical)
- (3) no chance for the flattish hand to show whether a minor slam try is feasible earlier on in the bidding

Examples:

- 1N--2N--3D--4D. Whilst 2N transfer shows !ds, the focus was on 3N / general game finding until 4D as a slam try was
  made
- 1N--2S--2N--3S--3N--4C. Shows !s singleton then bids onto 4C after 3N attempted sign off
- 1N--2S--2N--4C. Similar, late reveal of a slam try
- 1N--3C--3D--4m. Puppet Stayman then showing 5+ minor
- 1N--2C--2M--3m--3x--4m. Was finding best game until 4m implied slam interest
- 2N--3C--3D--4D. 4 level first time to show !ds, to even suggest !d slam try
- 2N--3C--3S--4D. Same, first time to show !ds. 4H only way to slam try !ss
- 1C--2D--3D--3x--4D. Similarly, game focussed opposite flat hand, until rebid 4m
- 1C--2H--3m--3x--4m. Same, only responder stronger balanced.
- 1D--2D--2H--2S--2N--3DHS--3N--4D. When the limited flattish hand could have 1--3 !ds, asking rather than Minorwood better
- 1M--2m--2N--4m. Again flattish opener, responder may want some indication of reject or accept

**** Flattish Q-Minorwood Variants 1 Bid Lower

Note there are some auctions where the bid below the minor suit shows a slam try in the minor suit. Responses are
similar just 1 bid lower:

- 1N--2N--3m--4C. Shows !d slam try with !c singleton, then similar
- 2N--4C. Artificial !d single suiter shown, then straight into the usual responses

*** 4CD vs Unbalanced Hands

Even when both hands are unbalanced, sometimes bidding 4m as RKB instead of 4m+1 (Redwood) makes much more sense due to
who is the auction's captain, who is (more) unlimited, or the general difficulty in setting trumps before being able to
use Redwood.

- game forcing constructive auctions
- Not just best game finding. Not preemptive. Not competitive
- 4m bidder is the captain, potentially unlimited (which is assumed if jump bidding 4m!). If limited and seeking
  cooperation then 4m is more general slam try last train like before Redwood
- nominally minor AGREED OR self JUMP 4m (re)bids showing good (often self-sufficient) hands
- EXCEPTION: [Flag Bidding](#Flag Bidding) situations, a non jump 4m flag bid is Q-Minorwood by the ideal captain
  (unlimited hand), e.g. 1H--1S--3C/3D, 1H--2D--3H--4D and other higher space consuming auctions

Some other exceptions due to the high start level of 2C/2D openings, the rebid of responders minor is Q-Minorwood.

- EXCEPTION: 2C--3C--3x--4m, 2C--3C--4C--4D
- EXCEPTION: 2C--3H--3N--4C either view as constructive skipping 3N game (an exception) or as a flattish limited opener and had limited
  space to check major before offering !c slam try (more normal Q-Minorwood situation)
- EXCEPTION: 2D--3C then further 4C rebid is assumed similar to jump 4m rebid quality


** Constrained Auto RKB

Some situations with limited space we may choose to signoff with bad holdings. Asker should have 2 keycards + Queen or
very reasonable high expectations of partner's keycard count to be safe.

- Sign off: 0/1 KC (maybe judged "bad" 2KC)

Step responses for the rest, skipping sign off bid:

- 2 no Q
- 2 with Q
- 3+ KC
- higher void + 2KC

Until further experimentation decides otherwise, Queen ask and King ask (4N minor, 5N major) are on if space permits.
Similar to EKB.


** Flag Bidding

Artificial bids to slam try from a selection of suits. Often when a two suiter has been shown. Sometimes we might bid a
minor at the 4 level naturally as the slam try, but a special bid is needed to slam try in the major at the 4 level.

"Flag bids (sometimes called "pointer" bids) are artificial bids that "flag" or point to one
specific suit among a known selection (often a two-suiter) as the potential trump suit for a slam try. They are
especially useful at the 4-level or higher when space is tight, you cannot naturally show interest in multiple suits
without bypassing key levels, or you need to distinguish slam interest in a major versus a minor."

When:

- Have not agreed the suit yet
- 4 level at least to agree
- Slam possibility

*** (1) 4C/4D Natural Flag Available

A less pressured flag bidding situation.

- bidding 4m naturally flags that suit, and may also be [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) depedending on who is unlimited
- the unbid suit flags the remaining suit
- other bids natural, e.g. to play in partner's major or rebidding our own suit
- after rebidding own suit instead of flagging, unbid suit flags it and either Constrained or Auto RKB follows
  depending on steps free

Very unlikely there would be 2 free suits to bid. Auctions such as 1C--2D--3D--3S--4C (!d + !s two suiter opposite
balanced GF) use either of the 2 free bids as implied cue bids because 3N is a natural possibility. Her 4C is an implied
cue bid. The balanced hand has at most 3 !ds. TODO update implied cue bid policy. Maybe Baron best on example instead of 3D if had !cs.

Examples:

2C--2D--3S = 6--5 !c + !s two suiter, flag bidder unlimited
    3N = natural, misfit
    4C = [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood), despite no prior agreement or jump, expected to choose a game
    4D = !s flag (implies bad !hs here else might 4N direct)
    4H = after 2D shouldn't have amazing !hs, so control bid and !s flag, imply poor !ds

2C--2N--3C--3S = 5--5+ !d + !s two suiter, opener wide-ish opening 10--15 hcp
    3N = misfit
    4C = excellent 7+ suit
        4H = !c flag, Auto RKB as 3 steps space free before game
            4S = 1/4 keycards
            4N = 3/0 keycards
            5C = 2 keycards no Q
    4D = natural flag, forcing
    4H = !s flag

2M--2N--3N = 6--4 !s + !c preempt
    4C = !c flag, [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) despite no prior agreement or jump
    4D/4oM = major slam try

(1H)--2H--2N--3S = Michaels !s + !d two suiter with extras, flag bidder unlimited
    4C = !s flag as natural 4m free for the other suit
    4D = [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood) despite no prior agreement or jump, expected to choose a game
    4H = control bid, suggests !c weakness, !s major implicit agreed

1H--1S--2N--3C--3H = 6--4 !h + !c two suiter hand, flag bidder unlimited
    3S = NF natural (3!s over 2N or bid a 4m auto-splinter if !s slam try)
    4C = natural flag, [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood), expected to choose a game or bid 3S
    4D = !h flag as natural 4m free for the other suit
    4M/5C = to play


*** (2) Flag Bidder Flattish Limited

- Flag bidder has no natural 4m flag available (e.g. just had 4m bid or rarely even higher)
- Flag bidder has no feasible long suit to (re)bid.
- Flag bidder is reasonably limited in strength
- 4N to play, it's a viable spot without a good fit
- LOW flag<->LOW GAME, HIGH flag<->HIGH GAME, partner should captain
- after flag the captaining bid is 4N Major RKB or NEXT FREE BID MINOR RKB
- only using NORMAL RKB instead of constrained because bidder is limited/defined we can guess their rough keycards
  before asking, so unlikely to propel self to high

The low flag<->low game, high flag<->high game policy prioritizes keeping 4N as major RKB (4M game lower than 5m game).

- It is NOT rank based flagging (not !c flag lower than other flags)
- It is NOT flagging based on keeping the flag below 4M whenever possible. Assumes should RKB if want to flag slam
- It is NOT step minimisation flagging (how constrained would the responses be when a follow up RKB ask happens)

Examples:

2N--3D--3H--4C = !h + !c two suiter, opposite flattish limited opener
    4D = !h slam try, lower game
        4N = RKB
    4S = !c slam try, higher game
        4N = !c RKB (03/14 responses, !c general RKB special case)
    4N = to play

2N--3D--3H--4D = !h + !d two suiter, opposite flattish limited opener
    4S = !h slam try, lower game
        4N = RKB
    4N = to play
    5C = !d flag (screwed for space)
        5H = !d RKB next free bid

2N--3H--3S--4C = !s + !c two suiter, opposite flattish limited opener
    4D = !s flag, lower game
        4N = RKB
    4H = !c flag
        4S = !c RKB, next free bid
    4N = to play

2N--3H--3S--4D = !s + !d two suiter, opposite flattish limited opener
    4H = !s flag, lower game
    4N = to play
    5C = !d flag (screwed for space)
      5H = !d RKB next free bid

*** (2b) Flag Bidder Flattish Limited, Freak Responder

- 6--5+ shapes where expected to play trumps
- 4N is an extra flag

1N--2N--3C--3S--3N--4H = freak 6--5 !d + !h hand with !s shortage (shortage showing implied slam try)
    4S = !h flag slam try, lower game
    4N = !d flag


*** (3) Flag Bidder Not Bid or Unbalanced

- Flag bidder has no natural 4m flag available (e.g. just had 4m bid or rarely even higher)
- 4N RKB for highest rank suit (not often a viable spot to play when slam possible)
- May want to show own good suit. If a rebid, then typically a good 7 card suit. If first chance to bid maybe a good 6
  card suit
- 1 flag free, for lower rank suit, the FLAG BID STARTS either Constrained RKB or Auto RKB

**** Auto Responses

- Auto RKB if 3 bids below 5 level trump suit (have room to bid 3rd step 2 no Queen and stay in 5m)
- Constrained Auto RKB if max 2 steps before 5m or 5M

Examples:

- !hs agreed then 4N is 3 steps below 5H so responses would be Auto RKB
- !hs agreed with 5C flag then 2 steps until 5H so use Constrained Auto RKB responses
- !ds agreed with 4S flag then have enough space so use Auto RKB
- !cs agreed with 4S flag needs Constrained Auto RKB

Standard RKB means 4N for majors or the nominal Redwood 4m+1 for minors.

With less than 3 RKB steps we need to compress our responses. With 3 or more before the trump suit then can use normal
Auto RKB step responses (auto RKB, responding without a separate ask). 3 steps is what you have with 4N as !h RKB - you
only go past the trump suit on the 4th step.

To compress responses play [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB). Rejects with limited keycards. Less nuance
than [Q-Minorwood](#Q-Minorwood), though might decide in context that 2KC no Queen is worth a downgrade.

Examples:

(2H)--3H = michaels !s + minor, SPECIAL CASE TURNS OFF USUAL STUFF (minor UNKNOWN)
    3S/3N = to play
    4C = pass/correct
    4D = good !s raise, similar to flag
    4H = control, good !s raise, implies a minor weakness
    4N = minor ask, slam interest (NOT usual RKB)

(2S)--3S = similar michaels + UNKNOWN minor, SPECIAL CASE TURNS OFF USUAL STUFF
    4C = pass/correct
    4D = good !h raise
    4N = minor ask, slam interest (NOT usual RKB)

(1H)--2H--(3H) = competition after michaels, SPECIAL CASE TURNS OFF USUAL STUFF (minor UNKNOWN)
    4C = pass/correct
    4N = minor ask, slam interest (NOT usual RKB)

(2H)--4C = GF leaping Michaels, !cs + !ss
    4D = !ds, natural forcing, own suit
    4H = !c flag, room for Auto RKB responses
    4S = to play
    4N = !s RKB
    5C = to play

(2S)--4D = GF leaping Michaels, !ds + !hs
    4H = to play
    4S = !d flag, room for Auto RKB responses
    4N = !h RKB
    5C = natural, to play
    5D = to play

(3D)--4D = majors bid two suiter
    4M = to play
    4N = !s RKB
    5D = !h flag, only 1 steps before 5 Trumps, use [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)

(3C)--4C = majors
    4D = natural
    4N = !s RKB
    5C = !h flag support, [Constrained Auto RKB](#Constrained Auto RKB)


